  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Because it was far",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. He reverts again to the description given in ver 7. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "That lieth by Beth-Rehob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "which belongeth to Beth-Rehob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the valley here spoken of was part of the territory of the Syrians of Beth-Rehob in the time of David (and very likely earlier), as we read in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It seems to have taken its name, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "House of Rehob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from Rehob the father of Hadadezer, king of Zobah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and to have been called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Beth-Rehob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " very much as Micah's settlement was called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Beth-Micah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It was also called for shortness ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Rehob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "as",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was situated, as we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the bounds of the tribe of Asher, in the extreme north of the Holy Land, near the entering in of Hamath, the site of which, however, is unknown (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The valley is that through which the Leddan fountain flows (ver. 7, note), and is the upper part of the plain called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "el-Hulleh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is the northern continuation of the Jordan valley. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They built a city",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "they rebuilt the city.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Judges 18:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And they (the Danites) had taken what Micah had made, i.e., his idols and his priest, and they fell upon Laish (על כּוא, to come over a person, to fall upon him, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 34:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), a people living quietly and free from care (vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), smote them with the edge of the sword (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 34:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and burned down the city (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 6:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as it had no deliverer in its isolated condition (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 18:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was situated \"in the valley which stretches to Beth-rehob.\" This valley is the upper part of the Huleh lowland, through which the central source of the Jordan (Leddan) flows, and by which Laish-Dan, the present Tell el Kadi, stood (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Beth-rehob is most probably the same place as the Rehob mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the Beth-rehob of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is there used to designate a part of Syria, and for which Rehob only is also used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 18:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Robinson (Bibl. Res. pp. 371ff.) supposes it to be the castle of Hunin or Honin, on the south-west of Tell el Kadi; but this is hardly correct (see the remarks on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Pent. p. 709). The city, which lay in ashes, was afterwards rebuilt by the Danites, and called Dan, from the name of the founder of their tribe; and the ruins are still to be seen, as already affirmed, on the southern slope of the Tell el Kadi (see Rob. Bibl. Res. pp. 391-2, and the comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]